responses: {"Experimenter":["Confirmed subject's identity (ID card)","Confirmed normal or corrected-to-normal vision","Obtained consent (signature and date)","Checked the test room lighting","Checked computer screen lighting","Checked distance from screen to chin rest (50cm)","Cleaned and adjusted chin rest","Counterbalanced the order of the tasks","Opened the experiment in Firefox","Made the experiment full screen","Encouraged subject to silence phone, put away distractors, etc."]}

{"Q0":"Once I settled into the task, it became immediately clear to me when a video was human or fake if there were people/words in the image that the agents were paying attention to. I felt like a human would default to looking at a face first, normally in the central part of the image, before scanning the rest of the image in a left to right fashion (in the way that English and many languages with similar alphabets are read left to right), or would move from foreground to background. Fake images would instead begin at those ending background/other objects points and then move their attention to the person or words on screen. Those images were easy to judge. It was more difficult to tell which agent was which when the attention patterns were less consistent with that which I just described, or if they started and ended their attention at the same point (or focused entirely on the people in the image, forcing me to then judge which person I would have focused on first to try to figure out which was the human condition)."}

{"Q0":"I found images with people, text, and obvious foreground/background elements the easiest to judge. I believe that humans will default to looking first at a human in an image before setting off on a scan of the image from left to right (especially if there is text to be read) or from the foreground elements to the background elements. The fake agent would step through these patterns backwards, which made it very easy to tell that it was fake as I don't believe a human would first look at a background, ignoring a human. It also felt easy when a screen was involved in an image, because I believe that humans have a natural curiosity if not a nosiness that would make them first look at what a screen might show before looking at any other element of an image."}

{"Q0":"I found it hard to judge images that did not feature humans, text, or anything particularly attention grabbing in the image. Then it was hard to find any pattern of viewing that I could believe is more human, as the scanning of the image would be more random than if there was something obvious that could draw a human's attention. There was also a specific image with two humans next to one another where the human agent only looked at the faces, back and forth. This meant that the fake agent's attention looked almost exactly the same, so I therefore had to decide which human would be \"more attention grabbing\" to try to deduce which agent was human, based only on the intervals that each human in the image was looked at with."}
